Nov 16 2009 	Five-star look and value with three-star service	Unlike Madonna, fellow 1980s icon Donald Trump has a hard time reinventing himself. Indeed, this Trump Tower Las Vegas has the look and feel of his guilded, brassed-up monoliths from two decades ago.However, the idea of getting a hotel suite like this for under $70 would be unimaginable. But The Trump Tower is one of those hybrid condo-hotels (where you never know who actually owns the unit you are staying in), and it does indeed offer a five-star caliber room with a mid-week pre-holiday rate at such a low price.That said, the service is ordinary at best. Simple requests for room items turned attempts to call housekeeping into the seemingly eternal abyss of the hotel phone system. Once the housekeeping is finally reached, the results are fine. The staff ably turned the sofabed (one in each suite) into a comfortable bed.Apparently, this hotel is the product of a Trump project gone the wrong way. Without a casino, this hotel has to fend for itself as a luxury hotel in a Las Vegas that is loosing its luxury customers fast. The result is to cut the rates as much as possible while cutting the service as minimally (or as invisibly) as possible.The toiletry items in the unit's spa-like bathrooms consisted of soap and skin cream. Hotel guests who know their way around five-star varieties also know that a bathroom with a separate oversized jacuzzi and a wide-screen color TV recessed behind the wall-sized mirror would also have a bit more on the vanity. Sure enough, an eventual call to housekeeping uncovered such goodies as sugar face scrub, exotic varieties of lotion, shower and bath gel and spa-quality bath salts. A $5 tip to the maid might ensure these items would be restocked the following day without another request.The hotel has a lunch restaurant on the wonderfully designed pool level, where well placed palm trees make the area seem like a summer oasis right off the Nevada mountains. The soups and salads are pricey at about $15 apiece, but they are well done and filling. The lobby-level restaurant simply prices itself out of use for most of the mid-week residents in early November. But those who can manage the nearly $30 breakfast buffet would be well rewarded with exquisite selections and friendly service in a setting that might very well be out of the most posh of design magazines. Room service was of high standard, too. But the best deal is to walk to Wallgreens and get breakfast items to use in the kitchenette.The $15 resort fee is a bit underhanded for a hotel that's not on a beach. But the extra fare came with fair warning during all stages of booking this hotel. I only wished the person checking me in didn't have to recite, with a straight face, that the $15 fee included two whole bottles of drinking water in addition to valet parking. Not even a bottle with &quot;Trump&quot; on its label is worth $7.50.A tip: Do NOT depend on the alleged shuttle service to the nearby Treasure Island Hotel and Casino. NOBODY seemed to know its schedule or even the process for getting one.	
