Oct 26 2009 	Nice hotel but know what your are getting	We stayed for a four night stay. If you are expecting a real five-star hotel, this is not for you. If you usually stay at a Marriott or Ramada, this will most likely feel like a five-star hotel. At a real five-star hotel, the doormen would never let you open your own door - here the doormen are sometimes manning the door. I can live with this, but some folks may have issues with this. Now the bathroom is top notch - nice shower, huge tub, and privacy door for the toilet, but there can be hot water issues. From talking with them, it seems they have boiler problems (again, a five-star hotel would not stand for this). The problem was fixed after a few minutes of letting the water run, but this too could upset you if you were not flexible. When we first arrived, we had a lower room (18th floor), but after reading these reviews, we asked for a higher room because of what we read about the train noise. Victor, the front desk manager, we very accomidating and relocated us to the 53rd floor on the city view side. From here, we barely heard the train - and the view was incredible.We got in late on the first night and tried the hotel restaurant and it had a $29 per person prix-fix menu that we tried. The food is actually really good.One night we wanted to eat at Paris' Mon Ami Gabi so we visited the concierge. Vicki was very helpful with the reservation and pulled some strings to get us a time that we wanted. Some of the other concierges come across snooty, but Vicki is top notch. We used the gym a couple times. It has everything you need to get a well rounded workout. No free weights, but they do have machines and dumbells. Treadmills, elliptical machines, and bikes have TV's built into them. They have trainers there to help you with the equipment if you have any questions. We also visited the pool. I thought it was nice. They had music playing and a DJ that tried to make it a fun atmosphere. My wife seemed to think that the waitresses were a bit snobby. We ordered a few drinks (sangria), which were refreshing. We would have ordered more, if our waitress paid attention to us. I also would have brought my own beer, but they do not allow outside drinks.Location to the strip is not too far, but can wear on you after awhile. It is about 5 minute walk to the strip, but another 10 to where the action really starts. Closest casino is Wynn or Treasure Island - for betting NCAA or NFL games on Saturday or Sunday morning by 9 or 10AM, this is a bit of a drag after a long Friday or Saturday night. We often used the mall across the street as a means to get to the Strip. The mall (they call it Fashion Show) is your typical mall with the usual suspects, some high-end. A real five-star hotel would not stand for this less than stellar location - they would have had a shuttle constantly taking you to the Strip.The only real nagging matter for me was the daily fee for internet usage. A real five-star hotel would not charge you for internet access. I already knew about the daily &quot;resort fee,&quot; so I did not have an issue with that. My guess is that they charge this separately because of a commission structure with the booking agencies and they cannot afford to discount this expense.If I go back to Vegas, would I stay here again? Probably not. I think I would rather be on the Strip. Am I disappointed with my choice? Not at all. We had fun and enjoyed the hotel, but I would rather be in the middle of the action. Some visitors may like this kind of place, though, so if the right person asked, I would recommend it.	
