Oct 17 2009 	Nice but not a 5 star hotel	We got a decent deal on Priceline for this hotel, for a recent three day trip to Vegas. However, watch out for extra charges! There is an additional $15 per room per day charge for valet parking (we didn't have a car) and use of the pool (didn't want to use it). The charge isn't optional however, so it's just a bit of a racket. The internet would have been an additional charge (didn't use it). Even though we got a good room rate, there weren't any affordable dining options here so we ended up going elsewhere as opposed to having $50 breakfasts. It would have been much more convenient to have a hotel with these kinds of facilities.The hotel is right directly on train tracks. At least on the &quot;City View&quot; side, you can vividly hear the train. We were on the 42nd floor. The trains woke us up 2-3 times per night. We live right on a busy 6-lane street at home, and yet the train was loud enough to wake even us up. To move to the other side of the hotel was going to be $25 per night extra (facing the strip instead of the city). In retrospect, it would have been worth it because of the train noise.The rooms are so nice - great bathroom with a TV embedded in the mirror, huge tub, huge shower, just great. Comfy cushy beds too. The concierge was super helpful, and got us great tickets to Penn &amp; Teller.A few quick notes:- There isn't a casino at this hotel- It's a 10 minute walk off the strip- There is a mini kitchen in the rooms (fridge, stove top, microwave, sink)It was a nice hotel, but for the cost/inconvenience factors, we won't return.	
Oct 15 2009 	Great Hotel - No Casino	Used Priceline to book a hotel on a quick business trip in Vegas. Went with 5-star for $85 and got the Trump. The hotel is really in a good location beside Fashion Show Mall. It is not actually on the strip but set back about a quarter mile. You can tell they had big plans to expand towards the strip but I guess the economy stopped that. It is hard to miss the white and gold tower from any where, so not hard to find.The lobby is very modern and elegant. Lots of gold that drives next the tacky edge but never goes over. I was there on a Wednesday night, so no crowded. Went right up to a desk clerk and was checked in quickly. Room on 50th floor facing north (downtown). They would have upgraded to a &quot;strip&quot; view if I would have paid another $25. No need.The room was great. These must have originally been marketed as condo rooms because the were large. This was a king room and the layout was one large room with bed, seating area and bathroom. The difference was that the room also had a large mini-fridge, sink and built-in cooking surface. Plates and silverware where provided. Very well appointed. The room was modern wood and metal. Very elegant. The bed was low to the ground and had lots of pillows and great linens. It had an ultrasoft mattress that was comfotable. The sitting area was large with a full couch and two comfortable sitting chairs around a full size cocktail table. The whole outside wall was floor-to-ceiling window that had a great view of the mountains. There was an ample desk with comfortable chair. The TV was a flat screen but it was small compared to what you would expect with the rest of the room. The bathroom was a real highlight. Large with seperate doored water closet, oversized jetted tub and huge walk-in shower. There were two large sinks in the vanity that was also huge. Everything was spotless. If you judge a good hotel room by its bathroom, this is one of the best I have seen. The toilet area and shower have textured smoked glass that is incredible. My only complaint is that the shower was so large, it could have easily taken another shower head either in the other wall or overhead along with a shower seat. It seemed a waste to have all that space without some extras. The location was great to get anywhere on the strip. I had not been to the Fashion Show Mall in years, but a quick walk across the street and there you were. Really nice and had a great dinner at the sushi restaurant at the front of the mall. Was there during happy hour (3-7pm) and everything was half-off. It was great.Note that the hotel does not have a casino. That is so unusual for any hotel in Vegas - especially one this nice. No long walks through the casino, loud noises, etc. If you like to gamble, you have to go across the street to the Wynn or on the other side of the mall to Treasure Island.I would stay here again. My wife would love it. If I took the boys it would be to boring.	
