May 21 2009 	Fine Hotel But Not Worth Staying Here	My wife and I went into the stay at the Trump with our eyes open (off the Strip, no gambling, etc.) and keeping an open mind. The problem was that even knowing those shortcomings and accepting them because of what seemed like a really good deal, there were just too many other issues to overcome.Check-in did not start off well. There was one staff person handling check-in, while there were at least five parties waiting for rooms. Another person did not come out for at least five minutes, by which time another five parties had arrived. Hard to believe there were not a few more employees in back who could have helped. When we were checked in and given the $50 spa credit that accompanied the room we booked, we were told that it was $50 off of a minimum $150 spa treatment. That was never made clear when we were booking the room. Seems like that would have been a point worth mentioning.The room itself was beautiful. New by Vegas standards, it was everything we were told it would be. Comfortable bed, chairs and couch, huge bathroom, and very nice kitchenette. Also, the no smoking policy was wonderful. That is the one true advantage to this property.While waiting for our luggage to be brought up, I noticed that there were no knives in the drawer with the other utensils. When the bags were dropped off, I pointed this out. The bellman offered to have them sent up immediately. We went down the gym (which was small, but certainly fine), came back to the room and still no knives. I placed a call to room service and was told someone would bring them right up. They never came. Housekeeping also did not replace them the next day (though they did remove/replace a dirty spoon we left in the sink). Long story short, it took TWO more calls over the next two days and asking for a supervisor in housekeeping before they were brought up. To me, that's just not acceptable in a hotel of this quality.While that was a minor annoyance, there was an even bigger problem: our &quot;City View&quot; room was about a block away from train tracks. Since the shades were generally closed, not a big deal. Except that every time a train approached, it blasted its whistle numerous times. This happened several times per night, and at least once during the day when we were in the room. I've stayed in nearly a dozen hotels on and off the strip in Vegas and this was the first time I was ever awakened by a train.The other main problem was the location. Train tracks aside, it is off the Strip. And yes, I knew that going in, but I guess I didn't realize what that meant. First, unless you wanted to eat at the one restaurant on-site, you had to leave to eat. Also, if you wanted to gamble, you had to leave to do that. Obviously, no shows or other entertainment. In short, it just didn't feel like Vegas. For some people that might be a plus. But my question is then why go to Vegas? Nothing is convenient. We walked to the Wynn one day by cutting through the mall, which is just across the street. But I can't imagine doing this when going out for the evening. I could not recommend this hotel, and won't be staying there again. Maybe the best way to describe it is &quot;removed.&quot; And that's not why we go to Vegas. The service was horrible, and resulted in even minor things becoming increasingly annoying when trying to enjoy a vacation. But if you are going to go, make sure to bring heavy duty ear plugs or ask for a room that is not near the train tracks.	
