May 4 2009 	Truly a V.I.P. experience -- well worth it if you can get a discount!	We were lucky enough to get a room here for ~$100/night (via Priceline); we probably wouldn't have been able to afford it otherwise. A neatly-groomed doorman greeted us and a friendly reception desk attendant checked us in. Another well-dressed staff member verified that we had a room key before we rode the elevator up. Our tastefully-decorated room was HUGE, complete with a single king-sized bed and a queen-sized pull-out couch. We had plenty of shelving and dresser drawers, a glass coffee table with a tic-tac-toe centerpiece, magazines and hardcover books. The 26th-floor view was amazing through the floor-to-ceiling window -- we could see snow-covered mountains in the distance. We had all the amenities: a huge LCD TV with remote and several cable channels, a mini-fridge, a coffee machine, two bathrobes, an iron, extra sheets, complimentary water bottles, newspapers delivered to our door, etc. The bathroom was a world unto itself: a huge glass partitioned shower with overhead shower head, another huge glass partitioned room with the toilet, a large spa bathtub, bright lighting (but not too bright), a cosmetic/vanity mirror, plenty of thick towels and soaps, a blowdryer, shampoo and conditioner, a plasma TV built into the mirror, dual sinks, etc. The doorman was even able to arrange for their courtesy shuttle to run us across the street to the Wynn. There were only a few CONS: some trash in the stairwell, a room service cart was left in the hallway for 1.5 days, no blanket could be found for the pull-out bed, and room service took ~30 minutes to deliver a &quot;Trump&quot; burger (albeit 3:30 AM) and &quot;dental kit&quot; (aka small toothbrush and toothpaste).Overall, excellent amenities and top-notch service!	
