Apr 14 2009 	Wow luxury and value all in one!	We checked in Thursday night around 10pm, there was no line, and the woman at the counter was very polite. I asked for a high floor and a strip view... she said they didn't have anything high, but she could upgrade me to a strip view. She assigned us to the 28th floor. It's pretty high for me, the view was great.The room (actually, the whole hotel) was beautiful. The room is huge, large wardrobes in the room, lots of drawer space, and a kitchenette with sink, fridge, microwave, stove, toaster, blender... and lots of kitchen tools. Every room has a jetted tub.Each pair of rooms shares an entryway, which is a little weird, but keeps the maid carts out of the hallways and adds to the luxurious feel of the hotel as a whole. There is a second (locked) door that leads to your room from the entryway.Train tracks travel N-&gt;S through Vegas, and pass every hotel on the west side of the Strip. This includes Treasure Island, Mirage, Caesar's ... even Bellagio. When there are train tracks next to your hotel, you can hear the train whistle -- this is not rocket science. Some reviewers here want to make it sound like a freight train is passing down the 28th floor hallway, and it's not like that at all. However, at night, with the TV off, you can certainly hear it. It didn't wake me up, but if you're used to the rustling of corn ears in Iowa, it might be a little loud for you.The walk to the strip is about 1/4 mile. The road is under construction at points, and there is not always sidewalk -- at one point you have to cross the street to pick up the sidewalk again. It is about 5 minutes from the hotel to the strip. Through the mall actually seemed longer, but distance-wise I can't swear to it. I have always stayed at one of the mega-hotels in the past, and walked my legs off to get from one point to the next, and Trump was no different in that respect.The $15 resort fee is a scam, but it is very popular these days. You cannot call ahead to have valet bring down your car, you have to go down in person. The two free bottles of water each day is a nice touch -- they are the perfect size to slip in your bag or jacket pocket before heading out for the day.Overall, I thought the hotel was a great value for the money we spent, and we'd stay there again, for sure. It is one of the nicest, most well-appointed hotels we've stayed at.	
Apr 13 2009 	Quiet Peaceful and Clean	This hotel is very peaceful. Mainly because it is off the strip. Just across the street from the mall in case you forgot any important items. Walgreens is also w/in walking distance. Quite a walk from most hotels aside from the Wynn/Encore. You have to take cabs EVERYWHERE from this hotel. Staff was very helpful. A maid came up to clean our bathtub @ 3am and was very pleasant. I only saw about 10 other guests the whole time, but it might be because of the time of year we went. There is also a complimentary Escalade truck that will drive you around. It was overall a good experience. Aside from the bathroom not being spotless when we arived, and it being VERY quite, it was a wonderful experience.	
Apr 10 2009 	Nice rooms; very poor service	The Trump seems like a good idea-- very low rates ($85 gets you a room and an upgrade to a 1 bedroom suite) and the rooms are very nicely put together. The problem is that the upside ends there. The location is not good at all. To get to the strip, you need to either walk through the Fashion Show Mall, or on Fashion Show Blvd., which has no sidewalks because it's a construction site. There isn't nearly enough staff to run the place properly-- nobody to hail you a cab at the curb, nobody to open the doors when you enter, nobody to help you with your bags, and so forth. Any request from room service or housekeeping took more than an hour to fulfill, without fail. Very disappointed. I was definitely left with the impression that I didn't get a deal-- I got what I paid for.	
Apr 9 2009 	Upgraded room was wonderful bonus!	We had a one-night stay at the Trump on April 4. We checked in around 8:00 pm and mentioned to the receptionist that it was our dad's first trip to Vegas. He upgraded our room to a one-bedroom premium suite overlooking the strip. We paid $100 a night for the room on Priceline. The room was listed on the hotel website for $350. What a deal!The room was gorgeous....the king size bed was extremely comfortable and the bathroom (with walk-in shower -- two shower heads!) was bigger than our one-car garage back home. We loved the TV built into the mirror in the bathroom! Very comfortable living room area with dining room table and kitchenette. We had to call for linens for the sofa bed. After one half hour, they did not arrive, so we placed a second call to the front desk and we had our linens within 10 minutes. We took advantage of the well-appointed gym but it was a bit too cold for swimming in the Olympic style pool. We loved the fact that there is no casino at the hotel....this was a huge plus! It made the hotel seem so much more classy and comfortable.$15 resort fee includes valet parking.	
Apr 8 2009 	Luxurious getaway smoke-free Vegas	Two girlfriends and I planned a weekend to Vegas, and I booked a studio suite at the Trump using Priceline for $88/night (plus tax and resort fees). I had read all the reviews on Trip Advisor before, so I called the hotel the night before our arrival to confirm our reservation and to request a room away from the train. The woman on the phone was delightful and happily agreed to accommodate my request.Check-in on Friday was a breeze--the front desk was fully staffed and we were waiting less than 5 minutes. The young man that checked us in was very friendly and when I asked him to confirm we were in a room far from the train, he said that he'd moved us to a better room and the train noise should be minimal. We were on the 50th floor with a view of the Stratosphere, and when we saw our room we were delighted that we had been upgraded to a 1 bedroom suite! The room was beautifully appointed, with 2 full bathrooms and a separate master bedroom. The master bathroom was absolutely huge!We enjoyed massages at the Trump spa, which were wonderful. The spa itself was smaller than expected, but nice. We asked for discounts on the massages and received $50 off coupons (the massages are $150 each for 60 minutes, so that saved a chunk). We did not use the gym or the pool, though the resort fee included use of both.Since we were a group of 3, two of us slept in the king size bed in the master bedroom and the third slept on the pull-out sofa. Housekeeping came and made up the pull out bed for us (upon request). The &quot;real&quot; bed was quite comfortable; my friend on the pull-out said it was just &quot;okay.&quot; The first night, the train woke up my friend who is a very light sleeper. I had earplugs in, so I didn't hear it at all. The second night, the train woke up both the light sleeper and me (even with my earplugs), but we fell back to sleep shortly thereafter. We were on the 50th floor (there are 52 floors total), so just plan on hearing the train, especially if you are on a lower floor.We didn't hear any of our neighbors at all; in fact, we never saw anyone else on the 50th floor all weekend.Housekeeping came once daily; we left our room by around 10am each day and by the time we'd return (around 3 or 4pm), the room was made up. The housekeeping staff did a great job, too. We really liked the idea of pushing a button to indicate the room was ready to be made up or to not be disturbed instead of hanging a sign on the door like every other hotel out there.We knew about the resort fee, and given the deal I got on Priceline, I really didn't mind paying $15/day. They noted that it included use of the gym, pool, and in-room stocking of coffee/water, and some other things I can't remember.On Friday night, there was a great lounge singer in the lobby by the bar and we enjoyed listening to him while drinking raspberry lemon drop martinis (very good). The wait staff and bartenders were really friendly and came over to chat with us.As for getting to The Strip, you have a couple options. There are always cabs waiting in front of the hotel, so you can take a cab. If you want to walk, the fashion mall is directly across from the hotel entrance, however, there is no pedestrian crosswalk, and you must cross with care (there is a surprising number of cars that drive fast past the hotel, so watch out). If you walk through the mall, it can take awhile as it is a little confusing inside, so I'd give myself 15 or 20 minutes to find The Strip. Note that the mall closes at 9pm, so it's not a late-night option. If you decide to just walk down Fashion Show Drive straight from the hotel to The Strip, it takes about 5 minutes (not 20 minutes as some reviewers have said, unless they are really slow walkers). Also, there is not an erotic museum between the hotel and the strip, despite what you may have read in other reviews on here, and there aren't crazy people lingering along the walkway, so I wouldn't call it &quot;dangerous.&quot; It is important to note that the sidewalk on the side of the hotel is not continuous, and as you get closer to the strip, you will have to walk on the side of the road, which is a little scary if the drivers aren't paying attention. In my opinion, it would behoove the hotel to finish paving the sidewalk all the way to Las Vegas Blvd. for the safety of its guests.If you don't want to walk or pay for a cab, the hotel offers a free shuttle to the Wynn between 4pm and midnight on Friday and Saturday nights. We didn't take advantage of it, but the doorman offered every time we walked out!On Saturday night, we walked down to The Mirage to see &quot;LOVE&quot; and it took us 30 minutes total, door to door. We are all in pretty good shape, but I don't think we were walking exceedingly fast (we were in heels!), so hopefully that gives you an idea of how far the Trump is from other hotels.All in all, the Trump is my new favorite hotel in Vegas. It was nice not to have my hair smelling like smoke all weekend, I didn't miss the &quot;ding-ding-ding-ing&quot; of slot machines in the lobby, and the staff went out of their way to make us happy. If the weather had been nicer, I would have loved to take advantage of the pool as it looked really relaxing. It was a great weekend and I will definitely stay there again.	
