Mar 8 2009 	This is a Five Star Hotel??	My husband and I recently stayed at the Trump during a business trip to Las Vegas. I was disappointed with the location, because to do anything, you must go outside and walk to shopping, dining or a casino. The Trump has one restaurant and a poolside snack bar and has no casino. I am not a wimp about walking, but the location did get annoying as the trip progressed.The rooms were fine, nothing special. The pool area looks similar to one you would find in your local gym with more seating and probably a slightly larger pool.My biggest problem with the Trump was the service. If this is the service one expects in a five star hotel, then I will happily stay at the Red Roof Inn. After being out of my room from 8:00a.m. to 2:30 p.m. I returned to find my room uncleaned and a message waiting for me. Housekeeping said they could not clean my room because the do not disturb button was lit. I explained to them that no button at all was lit because it was broken. They offered to clean my room immediately. I said great, I would go to the gym for an hour. After my time at the gym, I was starving but found the poolside snack bar was closed for a private party. Since I was very hot and sweaty, a trip outside the hotel for food did not seem like a good idea. I decided to take a shower and head out in the world for food. I got back to my room and it was still not cleaned. I called and they started talking about the light again. I explained that it was broken once again and they agreed to clean immediately. After a half hour of waiting, still no housekeeping. I went to the pool to get clean towels and threw my dirty towels into the hallway. After my shower I called housekeeping again. Once again we had the discussion about the light. They brought my towels, picked up the old ones out of the hallway and offered to clean my room. I told them I had to get dressed and dry my hair first.To make a long story a little longer, when my husband and I returned to our room around 10:00 p.m. it had still had not been cleaned. I made a call to housekeeping and just begged for some coffee for the morning. We talked about the light again, and I told them to never mention the light to me again. They did show up with the coffee and offered to clean the room, but I declined.Housekeeping was actually not my biggest complaint! We started out on the wrong foot with the bell desk at the beginning of our trip. My husband asked them to bring up packages to our room that had been delivered for his business meeting. We went downto the desk the next morning and they retrieved our boxes from storage, handed them to us and never offered to deliver them to our room. We were on our way out, but trudged up to our room with several boxes unaided.On the morning of our departure we called the bell desk to pick up our luggage. We had a ton of it because this was a multi city trip. After fifteen minutes of waiting we carried the luggage downstairs ourselves. I went to the bell desk and asked them where they had been. The bell captain looked confused so I said never mind. I did then ask him to retrieve our golf clubs out of storage. He brought the golf clubs to the bell desk, and then three bell people stood by talking to each other while I wrestled all of our luggage outside. (my husband was in a long line checking out). I thought they liked to help people so they would get tips, but it must work differently at Trump. I was actually making quite a disturbance trying to muscle the hard shell golf carriers out the revolving door, but no one saw fit to lend a hand.I would be really upset with this hotel if we had not only paid $114.00 a night for the room. We paid an economy price for economy service. You can get a room now for $89.00, and that is close the rate of a super budget hotel. You won't be disappointed with the service!If you want a real five star experience without a casino, try the Four Seasons at the other end of the strip. It is the top floors of Mandalay Bay, so it is convenient and a truly beautiful hotel.	
Mar 5 2009 	The perfect hotel for the Business Traveler w/ Vegas @ your doorstep!	I travel frequently for Business so my needs may be a bit different than the average Las Vegas Visitor. I am not here to party or gamble. I am here to work and the Trump International has provided me w/ a beautiful venue to do so.I have stayed @ the Wynn, Bellagio, Palazzo and Venetian and the rooms at Trump are comparable may even be a bit superior. Large and Beautiful!I love the fact that I have a fridge, stove top, microwave, coffee make, blender, toaster...etc. Many nights I would rather return to my room and make dinner, open a bottle of wine and not deal w/ the over priced cocktails and meals on the strip. Though I did treat myself to a Dinner @ Wynn one evening and @ Palazzo another.It was nice to return to the Trump after and walk through a quiet lobby...not one w/ screaming drunk party/gamblers on vacation.In the morning it's easier to make a quick breakfast and then head out to a days worth of meetings.The Trump International will stock your room w/ groceries if you want. I found it easier to stop at Whole Foods and pick up what I needed.Over all it was one of the best Business hotels I have stayed in!	
Mar 3 2009 	Great Rooms outstanding service but beware of the resort fee	We booked the Trump after the hotel picked up our bid on Priceline ($100/night for the weekend). We were hoping to get the Wynn or the Venetian, as we did on our last trip. So, initially, we were a little bummed, particularly after reading that the Trump had no Casino, charged a $15/night mandatory resort fee, and was a bit of a walk to the Strip. It turned out, though, that none of these things were a very big deal and we had an excellent stay at this property. The walk to the Wynn/Strip is a short, pleasant, 5-minute jaunt. Moreover, you can enter Nordstrom’s across the street and walk through the mall to the strip. We also found the Trump lobby to be pleasantly scented, which we much preferred to the ubiquitous cigarette smell that perpetually wafts through all Vegas casinos. The resort fee, on the other hand, is lame (if you have no choice but to pay, they should just include it in the price of the hotel rather than make their guests feel that the hotel is trying to cheat them out of a few bucks). However, it does come with some nice perks such as late check-out, a choice of a range of newspapers, 2 free small bottles of water per day, use of the pool and access to the fitness center.Concerning the paper, we did get the Sunday NY Times (eventually), which I would have had to search all over town for and buy for $5. On Monday, though, I received no paper. I’m sure a call to the front desk would have rectified this, but I still had the NY Times magazine from Sunday, so didn’t bother. We also made use of the late check-out (until 4pm), which is convenient if you have a later flight. We never tried the pool or the fitness center, but hear both are quite nice.The service at the trump is outstanding! Over the course of our stay, I requested extra clothing hangers, a down pillow, regular coffee (we only had de-cafe in our room) and a newspaper (on Sunday the times hadn’t yet been delivered at 7am, but they said they would run a copy up as soon as it arrived); all items were brought immediately and the operator, Jasmine, was very pleasant. In fact, everyone we spoke with at the hotel was very kind and accommodating. The only slight exception is the maid service. In addition to not providing regular coffee, they failed to refill our conditioner (which was empty). The studio suites at the Trump are among our favorites on the strip. We still slightly prefer the rooms at the Venetian (we like their living room area a bit more and prefer the extra flat screen to the half kitchen – it’s more esthetically pleasing if less functional). The Trump, though, has a far superior bathroom (a Jacuzzi tub and a cool TV built into the mirror) and the fridge in the kitchen/living room is a nice touch. The beds are very comfortable and, provided you get a suite facing the strip, the views are spectacular. We were in 2827 and had an incredible view of the Encore, the Wynn, the Palazzo, the Venetian, Treasure Island, and the Mirage. Strip view rooms are supposed to be an extra $40/night, but we politely requested an upgrade at check-in and they gave it to us. While it’s clearly a 5-star resort, I don’t think it’s worthy of a 5-star review given the resort fee, the coffee, conditioner and newspaper. These are obviously very small issues and I expect they won’t have much impact on most readers’ stay.For those that stay at the trump, I would like to pass on a few of additional recommendations. Esthetically, the Encore casino (about a 6-minute walk) is our favorite on the strip. Rather than the dark drabness of most casinos – which can make one feel a bit claustrophobic – the Encore is bright with high white ceilings; cool red chandeliers; and richly-colored, upholstered walls. My favorite poker rooms, though, are the Wynn and the Venetian. Both have top-notch dealers, complimentary drinks with many top-shelf liquors (if requested), and over a dozen flat screen TV’s, etc… We also liked Dal Toro for breakfast. It’s at the Palazzo, with outside seating and good eggs benedict – they use toasted sourdough and some parmesan cheese, which is a nice twist. We didn’t like the buffet at Beliggio, though. The food was just okay and the ambience is that of a Denny’s. It may be worth the $15 on weekdays, but not the $25ish on weekends. If you want to do a buffet, I recommend paying the extra few dollars and going to the Wynn.Happy Travels,Jason	
