Jan 14 2009 	Awesome hotel but still working on some service issues.	Let me start off by saying we were completely thrilled with this hotel. I was not sure how I would feel about staying in Vegas in a hotel without a casino but thought I'd give it a try since the price was right and most hotels were booked (we were there for CES). Upon arriving we experienced the quiet sophistication of a high end hotel with out the loud slot machines, lights and cigarette smoke Vegas is known for. The check in was painless, the staff at the front desk was very polite. Going up to our room we were pleased to find we were on the 58th floor, facing the strip. This made for an absolute beautiful view at night as we could see clear from one end of the strip all the way down to Mandalay (the opposite end), it was truly a spectacular view. The room was very large, well appointed, a very comfortable bed, a couch, chairs, coffee table, desk, microwave, fridge, cooktop, blender, toaster, big closets, lots of drawers. All this and the room did not feel cramped at all. The bathroom was gorgeous, very big marble, flat screen in the mirror, enormous tub, beautiful shower. I also like the location of the hotel. It is set a bit back from the strip, yet is right across the street from Fashion Show Mall, and on the other side of the street is the Wynn, Palazzo, and Venetian. The Bellagio is a painless 1 mile walk (or 8 dollar cab ride). Anyway point being, we went to those hotels to gamble and then did not have to walk back through a casino to get to our room, or in the morning. Ok now to the service issues. Before arriving at The Trump I attempted to make use of the renowned &quot;attache services.&quot; I was requesting they fill our fridge with beverages we wanted during our stay. I e-mailed and after a couple days heard back. I had a couple questions and she never responded back. I thought this was disappointing as it is touted as one of the highlights of the hotel. Annoying. Upon arriving to our room, our fridge had something spilled in it (yuck), and our water bottles which are supposed to be in each room (as part of the &quot;resort fee&quot;) were not there. The gentlemen who brought our luggage checked these things and appeared very unhappy with the oversights, again he was very kind and assured us it would be taken care of, and it was. Our friends were also missing the water bottles out of their room, as well as a bathrobe. These may seem insignificant but for a hotel that really prides itself on its service, we a little surprised at the oversights. I did order room service and it came very quickly and was delicious but set my tray in the hallway to be picked up (around 3 in the afternoon) and when we left to check out the next morning it was still there. Overall the employees that we came in contact with were VERY nice and helpful, it were the ones you didn't see who seemed to not be doing their jobs. Perhaps it's a sign of the economy and they just don't have enough people on staff?	
