Jan 4 2009 	NYE 2008 Reviewed	We stayed at the Trump Hotel Las Vegas for New Years 2008 from12/29 to 01/02/09. The room was a corner 1BR suite located on the 45 floor with views of the Central and North Strip.The Hotel is conveniently located off I-15 and Spring Moutain, a few twists and turns and your there. Shoppers will love the location as it's located directly across form the Fashion Mall and you can enter by foot through Nordstroms, however there is no cross walk or better a skywalk, so be prepared to dodge some traffic or walk up the street a bit to a cross walk at the light. The Valet Staff while slow is professional and curteous. The front Desk staff is professional and check in was quick, but our arrival was after peak. Be prepared to be slapped with an extra $15.00/day fee for pool, gym, valet and what ever else they try to throw in like 2ea. complimentry bottled waters per day. Funny the pool was drained for the season. This is not disclosed on their website reservations. The hotel lobby, bar and lounge are nice with open and spacious construction. The actual bar is really small for a place this size.The 1BR suite room was nice and spacious as well. The corner suites have a private entry foyer located off the main interior hallway which elimanate possible walk by noise from late returning party's. Unless you have been distrubed by this in the past at other hotels you may not appreciate this rare feature. The kitchenette's are small but sufficient and the sub-zero refrigerators are nice with built in ice maker. The kitchens contain all basic essentials plus some, including blender, toaster, mircowave, stove and diswashwer. The dining room table is adequate and the living room is spacious with nice built in entertainment center and L shaped sofa/sleeper. There is a 47&quot; flat screen in in the living room although it had a picture and sound glitching problem the staff could not fix. The hall bathroom was spacious with its own shower. The master bedroom was very spacious with his/hers closets ironing boards, sitting chair and ottoman. The master bedroom has a 32&quot; flat screen that worked without problems. The master bath was huge, the size of most deluxe rooms on the strip with Jacuzzi tub, shower for 2 easy, his/her sinks and seperate water closet. The mirror in the master has a cool 13&quot; TV screen built in. Negatives: The heating system was not adequate to heat the suite especially in the bedroom. Two calls and two HVAC technicians later the problem was not resolved. The bedding was all down comforter, bed pad and pillows. I guess the hotel does not anticapte that some guests cannot tolerate down as they have no substitute bedding, except for pillows. We went without mattress pad and comforter. The staff delivered what I would call thick sheets and called them blankets. The suite was not as clean upon arriving as would normally be expected. There were hairs, crumbs etc. on counters and in the sinks, refrigerator etc. The living room had an area that reeked of bad colone. The staff will honor the &quot;do not distrurb&quot; sign by not knocking on your door, but they will ring your room after 3PM for acccess and then not show up for a few more hours. So unplug your phone or turn the ringer off if you truly want to catch some extra Zzzz's or what ever before venturing out for the night. The 47&quot; flat screen in the living room may as well have not been there as it was impossible to watch and I guess impossible to fix as it remained as such after the repair staff &quot;looked&quot; at it. The most comical part of the stay was the reaction of &quot;senior&quot; room service staff which we had the pleasure of dealing with twice. Unholding the standard the Trump adds an automatic $5.00 per person surcharge plus a whopping %18 gratuity to all room service charges. So when I get a suprised look from a room service person for not adding &quot;extra&quot; gratuity to an already over inflated bill for strolling up some food, I just have to smile Not once but twice. Cracks me up just thinking about it again.Oh, yea got the Wall Street Journal and Las Vegas Review Journal delivered to the door every morning. Nice perk. Actually read an article in the WSJ during the stay coincendentially after just seeing an infomericial of Trump hawking real estate how to seminars that he just defaulted on a $53M loan payment which has already been extended twice for him on one of his property endeavors. Stating the default was to preserve &quot;liquidity&quot;.Bottom line: Nice hotel. At the price point they have some superior competition though. They need to work some kinks out fast or deal with the consequences.	
Jan 4 2009 	Nice Room but It's the Little Things...	I'm a fan of Las Vegas Condohotels, and have stayed in all of them that have opened so far. In terms of the room only, the Trump is nice. It's very similar to the Signature, though with slightly less square footage and no balconies. The room fittings may be of slightly higher quality than the Signature, beautiful sinks in the bath and lots of tasteful marble. Rooms are a couple of years newer than the Signature, so may be fresher.We checked in just after 3pm on New Years Day. The front desk attendant was pleasant, but said our room wasn't ready yet.  We really didn't feel like waiting -- there were a lot of people in the lobby obviously already waiting for their room, so I asked if there were any upgraded rooms available. We ended up upgrading to a premium corner suite 1 bedroom for another $100 a night so we wouldn't have to wait. Our room was on the 19th floor and had a bathroom as big as the bedroom, with a large window over the tub. Unfortunately, the view was mostly of the freeway and parking lots. Would've been cool to have a higher floor and strip view...The Trump charges $15 a day now in a resort fee which I wouldn't have minded -- if internet was included -- but that's an extra $12 a day (again, the Signature fee includes wifi). The resort fee includes bottled water and coffee -- the water wasn't replenished the 2nd day, there was only 1 coffee cup in the kitchen, and the only creamer available was a hazelnut cream cremora flavor. Bed and linens were the least comfortable of any high end hotel I've stayed in in the past year, including the Palazzo, Palms Place, and the Sig. Room service took an hour and a half to arrive. Food was good quality, but by the time it got to us we wished we'd just gone out for breakfast. In sum, the hotel is a beautiful facility, clean, and it should be excellent, but it's obviously understaffed, and too many little things added up to make it a really good hotel. If the Signature is maintaining their rooms well, it's much better managed in every way. Even the Palms Place, with the rough start we had in our stay there, seemed better managed and had a much more interesting room...	
