Oct 6 2008 	BE WARNED! In no way fun for the typical Visitor!	First, Didn't realize this was a condo building with Trumps name on it? Although they rent these units out as hotel rooms, this is in no way a typical Vegas Hotel. They should have left it as a condo building for residents only &amp; not opened it to the typical tourist. The overall feel is like visiting your old grandmother on Park Ave: a high-end unit to sleep only &amp; find any reason to get out! Simply nothing to do!Although this just might appeal to the older crowds? Meaning: it's smoke-free, non-gaming, &amp; extremely quite. (except the train honking at all hours of the night). Like every other hotel I have stayed at in Vegas they have endless amenities to keep you from visiting the next hotel. Don't expect a cab to be waiting outside when you decide to go out (OFTEN). There is no cab stand. This hotel isn't on the strip so you will need to walk about 10mins to the nearest hotel. And if you drive, expect a mandatory $14 parking fee. (no-self parking)!So some more of my frustrations &amp; lack of amenities. Only two front desk clerks so check-in took&gt;30mins. Room was spacious with a kitchenette but had no mini bar? So this hotel has over 1200 rooms but only one restaurant/bar, &amp; located in a museum like lobby? Which was very very quite! Oh and it doesn't stay open late. And forget about room service as it wasn't available after 1am? The only attractions are the pool area &amp; spa/fitness room. The one &amp; only pool is very basic &amp; small, but did include a lounge area with bar &amp; tvs. Again very quite &amp; lack of people? Finally the fitness center. Nice cardio machines but limited weight machines &amp; free weights. Oh, &amp; it's $22! (with an empty frig &amp; empty water cooler). Very annoying not to have water when working out. The spa didn't open until 9am so had to walk down the hall to get water from a warm water fountain. Like every hotel I have been too in Vegas there was always excitement in some way. Of all places, Circus Circus could do a better job of entertaining, seriously! If you're into extreme quite, very few people to see/be seen, &amp; lack of amenities, give it a try. Don't say you weren't warned if you do stay here &amp; ask yourself &quot;Am I in Vegas?&quot; _____________________________________	
Oct 4 2008 	Is this really a 5 Star?	The Trump Tower shines like a beacon when you get on the strip going north from the airport. That may have been the best part. It is located on the north side of the Fashion Show Mall. There is nothing else out there so it sits in the middle of ugly. We were told the construction in that area has been halted because of the economy.The lobby is large but empty and austere. Not at all welcoming. The employees were all very nice.We booked through Priceline and were bidding on a 5 Star hotel. We expected the Venetiian or the like. When we were told it was the Trump Tower we were shocked because there is no casino, live music or any type of entertainment. It's like a morgue.Plan on paying an extra $15 a day for valet. They offer no self park.We paid $121.00 per night plus the $15. We could have booked right through the Trump for $159. So no big deal in savings there.We chose the 17th floor. That is where the rooms start. If you go there, choose a higher floor or you will have a very limited view.The room was very nice with a well appointed kitchen. However there is no table to sit and drink a cup of coffee at. The bathroom is devine and the spa tub is luxurious.All rooms are suites and have one king bed and one queen sleeper. There were three of us so one of us had to sleep on the sofa sleeper. Yuk! This is not 5 star business! The king bed was as hard as a rock.The place seems deserted. There seemed to be only one other guest on our floor the whole time we were there. I can't imagine this place staying in business.If you gamble, go to Tuscany it is fun and you can win. Also, go to the Wynn. We earned 4 free buffets there for very little money. The food was wonderful.I would not stay at the Trump again.	
Oct 2 2008 	Great stay at this fabulous hotel!	My husband and I booked this hotel through Hotwire and were unsure of how we would like the property when we got there after staying for 2 nights previously at Caesars. I had stayed before at the Trump Tower in Atlantic City and remembered a lot of gaudy gold surroundings, but not much else other than the clean room. We were pleasantly surprised when we got to the Trump Tower, especially for the price ($144 per night)! First of all, the hotel is brand new and not crowded, unlike some other hotels on the Strip. The service from the moment we stepped out of the taxi was excellent from the doormen to the front desk to room service. Our room was great and I generally consider myself picky. The bathrooms are fantastic with a nice shower, a large tub, and a TV in the mirror on the vanity. The room itself has nice furnishings and was very comfortable -- even for a pregnant woman like me! The pool was a nice break from screaming revelers and children at other hotels. Most of the lounges had sun shades and the bar and wait staff were very attentive in terms of bringing out food and drinks promptly. Our room service order was delivered within 15 minutes of ordering it and was delicious. I also appreciated a reprieve from all of the smoking at the other casinos. There are some things to consider depending on what type of Las Vegas experience you are looking for:1. There is no casino which my husband and I are fine with since we are not big gamblers, but if you came to gamble you might not enjoy it so much (or at all). The Wynn is a very easy 10 minute walk from the hotel. It might seem farther than it is when you first come down the street. 2. Extremely limited shopping and restaurants in the hotel itself. The Fashion Show Mall is directly across the street though.3. Room service menu is limited.4. Some of the amenities are limited, perhaps because the hotel is relatively new? I asked for bubble bath since the tubs in the rooms are perfect for relaxation, but they did not have any. The Front Desk said that this is a common request and that they would be correcting it within the next month.5. I did hear the train once in the middle of the night that some previous people had written about, but I personally thought it was no big deal. We were on the 27th floor facing the Strip so maybe location does matter?Overall our experience was outstanding, considering we paid 4X what we paid for this room at Caesars for the same level of room quality. If you are looking for a different Las Vegas experience outside of the standard casino/hotel fair and do not mind staying away from the action, I really do recommend the Trump.	
Sep 28 2008 	Above Average But Not For The Average.	My wife and I stayed at the Trump Tower, Las Vegas for a week long work conference at nearby Wynn. Although the rooms were rather exquisite, the extra charges for average amenities were outrageous! A daily charge for Wi-fi usage, a daily charge for gym equipment usage, etc., (standard inclusions provided at much simpler hotels) kept us from thoroughly enjoying our surroundings and relaxing (also, not noted as requiring an additional surcharge on their website). After visiting many of the other casinos/hotels within a one block radius, we noticed the lack of atmosphere at the Trump and could only summarize it to be just &quot;another expensive hotel&quot;. A side note - our camera was held for us at the bell desk overnight and found to have additional photographs upon check out the following morning.	
Sep 26 2008 	Luxurious....but a couple of problems....	We stayed in the Trump for 3 nights and were very impressed with the luxury of our room. The jacuzzi bath was fabulous and the room was spacious and very well decorated. There is no casino or restaurant in the Trump which could be a problem if you want the whole Las Vegas atmosphere in your hotel. However, we were quite happy to go to the other hotels for rthat and come back to the peace of the Trump. You also have to pay extra to use the gym.The location isn't great. It's at the far end of the strip and it takes a fair while to walk to the major hotels and casinos. I didn't think this would be a problem but walking long distances in the heat isn't much fun. There are lots of taxis around though should you wish to use them.Our major problem with our room was the noise of a freight train blaring its horn throughout the night. Myself and my husband woke up everytime it sounded, which was on the hour from 3am. We asked to be moved and were relocated to the other side of the hotel facing the strip. This was much quieter. It was odd that we had been allocated the room in the first place as the hotel was not full and the receptionist was very aware of the rooms which were most affected by the horrendous noise.So, overall a fabulous, luxurious hotel aside from the location &amp; that train!	
